		Comment <a href="#c_1713670425">7</a> by Brian Kotek
		posted on 8/17/2007 at 9:03 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>I've found that by far the best way to really, deeply understand something is to write about it and teach it to other people. You might think you know something well, until you try to explain it to someone else. That is when every hole in your knowledge will become glaringly obvious. So teach others. Write a blog. Talk at a user group. Record an online presentation. Whatever works for you.</p><p>Also, read. A lot. Read the Pragmatic Programmer. Then read it again. I read this book about once a year and I learn or understand something better every time. Play with other languages. You get the idea.</p><p>With regard to working on a team vs. individually, I'd say all things equal, work on a team. You will probably learn more. However, there is a certain power (and risk of course) in building things yourself. You get to experiment to your heart's content. Of course, when things go wrong, you don't have to look far for the person to blame. ;-)</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
