		Comment <a href="#c_1713670421">11</a> by Thomas Messier
		posted on 8/17/2007 at 10:20 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>I've done both solo and team projects, and IMO both of them are valuable. When working solo, I had to take responsibility for things I wasn't as comfotable/knowledgeable about, forcing me to go the extra mile to learn them well in order to come up with a quality product. On the other hand, working in a team you get to benefit from the knowledge of others. All those invaluable little tips, from keyboard shortcuts to IDE settings to design patterns to whatever else. Right now I work mostly solo, so I basically resort to reading tons of blogs. I go though my RSS reader about twice a day, and I have to say there is some invaluable information being shared on many blogs. Ray's is one. Others among my favorites, in no particular order, are Brian Rinaldi, Joe Rinehart, Peter Bell, and Ben Nadel. There are many others. Take the time to read them, especially when you're working solo, those people will replace your co-workers for advice. And they do it well.</p></div>
